reviews.review_text:
Cop a Copps
A dual-keys show at their final stop outside the U.S. Though a high point for the era returned in June, this is considered a high mark of the March tour. Fairly impressive for a '92; a top ten for the year. First Set. Hellina is a warm up; the mix is not set yet, Jer's a bit off. With the cement poured, Althea is cooler than a January popsicle. The Same Thing can be counted on in '92/'93, when it reached a peak, and this is an example. There's a mic problem for Jer in Brown Eyed. The rest of the set is average, except for a quite solid Bird Song. Second Set. Jer struggles with the verses on Shakedown Street, but not the playing – the second half is kewl. Dewiminna has Bruce on accordion, which some liked at the time and some felt was not very "Dead". Dark Star is the second of just six in '92. It's good, if rather safe. Increasingly from this point forward, Drums>Space got better while all others declined. This Space is indicative of that direction: a big psychedelic, sci-fi version. The Other One is the peak of the back nine. Dig the crazy shite Bobby plays on rhythm (his speak-shout and rounyalnow, not so much). Standing on the Moon is almost a wash until Hornsby comes in, then there's a nice end solo. You get MIDI horns on Love Light. Bruce is the best part of U.S. Blues, though Bobby's feedback/warble chords really work here. 1st Set:  B- 2nd Set: B- Overall = 3½ stars Highlights: Althea – fine version The Same Thing – '92 is a good year for it, featuring this example Space – big psychedelic/sci-fi version SOURCES: There's a great matrix (seamons_95208) if you want a livelier feel. The SBD update is 141806_sbd_miller, however it runs too fast, needing -2% pitch correction. The whole show is on 30 Trips. Althea is on Definitive Live. Most of the show is usually up on YouTube, in grainy, handheld quality.
